But jumping to the end of that sector in buggy flash, and 4k ahead in the firmware blob, they don't match up again. Jumping one 4k sector ahead in each in tandem, I can't find a point where they start to match up again.
I think I do need to track down a dump of the flash >_<
I do have U6 Pros. I will see if I can figure out how to dump the flash. If needed, I can unsolder the ROM to dump it.

So either a whole lot of my flash is corrupt (someone else pointed out on the bottom, after they start diffing, entropy drops immensely, havn't done any testing over the dump to see if its consistent the rest of the way, but its only data in that one sector that reads differently each time I read it), or my failure is _right_ at the boundary of some data stream

almost all of them have ~500 byte differences between them, all in the range of 0x7c000 - 0x7cfff which is why I thought just that one 4k sector was hosed.
Wow, that is strance. I have never seen anything like that before, and I have dumped like 10 chips lol.

And the fact that I can read more than a sector and that is valid data from 0x0 till that 0x7c000 sector start, and that is also more than the full page of that chip, I think the flash itself underneath failed rather than some controller IC failure
yeah, I've never seen flash fail in this way
I spent a good couple of hours trying to dump the chip with different devices too, they all got roughly the same data, aside from that chunk of bytes that were randomish every read

I only have the one known good dump. But yeah, I'm going to do some testing on it and see what it does and how it behaves. Need to read the OTP data off it too
yeah, seems like an an board issue where the flash chip or its interconnects failed
Its not very old, year or two. I think it got a botched firmware update

Thats the only reason I can think of a few pages of good data, then some sector that didn't get a clean erase/write in a state of nomansland when reading the flash cell, then the rest of the data garbage

yeah, I'm thinking its a botched update. In looking closer at binwalk info, I see a valid dtb in my dump (there _are_ some valid chunks in my dump after the 0x7c000 area, so, it might not be corrupt to the end of flash) and the dtb there is dated in 2022. Will do testing of the actual flash tomorrow
can you do a write to the flash chip or is it too much of a PITA to de/resolder? If it was just faulty power during an update and you can get a good one to work, problem solved?

not sure the level of issue you're having, but if you're able to dump the flash and you can write to/read from the bad sectors and get correct data, then it seems like you can solve the issue before the end of the day
earlier, I thought you were saying you didn't get the same read from those sectors, repeatedly, which indicates to me a bad connection
Its still currently desoldered. I dumped it that way directly. I havn't tried yet to erase/rewrite the new dump from seeigecannon.

Ah, no, sorry for confusion. The dumps I _was_ getting, saw bytes in some 4k sector reading random values on each read, but the rest of the data around it was reading the same every time. So first ~500kbytes read the same (and match the dump I got from seeigecannon), a 4k sector would get different values in some bytes each read, and then the rest of the chip appeared to have some data corruption (friend of mine called out that parts of the data dump after the screwy sector appeared to be fairly low entropy).
If I had to guess, the update probably was doing some page/sector erases and updates, and probably got a power cut during one stage of that leaving the sector in a bad state.
Out of curiosity, is it possible to recover from that (i.e. erase and rewrite or something) or is that chip permanently fried?

No clue. I've never seen flash fail in this way, which kind of leads me to believe it is a transient error and can be cleared by a proper erase and write. The random data reads from some bytes really hints that the individual flash cells were not fully charged or discharged properly and reads of the bit are causing metastability when the controller is processing it. The rest of the data remaining unchanged between reads, really hints that the flash is _probably_ okay, just, has incorrect contents.

This caused an unexpected flashback to some Win 2k/xp machines that would cache such an operation on a block storage device, so you could get timing-inconsistent behavior if you were to remove the device, even after "verifying"  the data

I "fried" something like 30-40 MicroSD cards to test and document the behavior

I was tasked with ejecting them as soon as the device reported a write was finished and validating the data. I call them "fried" because they stopped meaningfully enumerating on the system - no drive nor volumes nor devices showed up, as if an internal fuse had blown and permanently disabled the cards. Most failures were much simpler - card often needed to be reformatted and there'd be some block that was corrupt because a write operation was interrupted mid-cycle

Update!

I think I've narrowed down what happened with my AP. It looks like it may have experienced a power failure updating from 6.5.62 to 6.6.56. I grabbed the firmware update files for every release that I could for the U6 Pro, found where in the update file the broken sector I saw in my flash ends up going and how long and doing some comparisons. Here is some info on it:

```
$ binwalk BZ.ipq50xx_6.6.77+15402.240813.0345.bin 

DECIMAL       HEXADECIMAL     DESCRIPTION
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
...
152924        0x2555C         Ubiquiti partition header, header size: 56 bytes, name: "PARTQSEE", base address: 0x00050000, data size: 593388 bytes
152980        0x25594         ELF, 64-bit LSB executable, version 1 (SYSV)
```

The erroring sectors I was seeing started at `0x7c000` which is inside the QSEE partition. Whatever that is.

When I do a comparison in a loop of my broken file against all of the QSEE partitions stripped out of the update files:
```

Ultimately, yeah, I'm very confident there was a power loss/glitch during update. There are a few main sections that binwalk notes in the flash dump. The first section is some early boot, and I see this matches bit for bit the same named section in the firmware update blob for newer firmwares; namely starting at 6.6.65. The next section is where the update failed, the first half of it matches newer firmware update blobs for that section, then the glitchy sector, then the rest of the content matches older firmware update blobs, from < 6.5.x

Unfortunately, I can't pin down a single firmware release. The flash isn't changed every update. e.g. that first section in my flash, across all firmwares for this AP, there are only 3 different releases for that first flash section. The most I can narrow it down to is two "groups" of firmware updates, one group is 2 releases, the other group is 6 releases. So. I think I'm going to make two copies, one the latest of each "group" patched in to the first flash segment, and then repairing the glitches flash segment (which will have the same contents across both of those flash groups).
